sentence: I feel like I need to die to be happy.
reframing1: There are some things I don't like about myself, but there are also some things I do like about myself. I can focus on those when I feel bad about myself.
reframing2: My body does some amazing things. I don't always have to love the way it looks, but I can still be grateful for the things my body does for me.

sentence: I am not the kind of person that she would like to go out with.
reframing1: I don't know what she is looking for in a potential partner. I should like her on the app and see what happens.
reframing2: I am assuming that there is nothing about me that would be attractive to her. There are many different parts of what make me who I am.  Everyone has strengths and weaknesses - I am not the only person with some faults.

sentence: I feel horrible about it, I must be a bad parent
reframing1: I'm feeling horrible for saying no, but that doesn't necessarily mean I'm a bad parent. I may need to be harsh at times, but there are also times when I'm gentle and kind
reframing2: I'm feeling horrible, but a good parent is harsh when they need to be

sentence: My husband doesn't want to spend time with me.
reframing1: I can express feeling left out to my husband, and that I would like us to have time to connect later this week. I can have a conversation with him instead of making assumptions about what he's thinking.
reframing2: I spend a lot of time with my partner and maybe he wants some connecting time with a friend. I have a healthy relationship with my partner.

sentence: They are so wrong and I'm so pissed but I know I can't prove it and they will probably win because they won't ever admit it and I have to do something right NOW! or I might lose my dogs.
reframing1: Maybe we can talk to the neighbor to figure out what happened.
reframing2: i'm not going to lose my dogs. I can bring them indoors next time.

sentence: I am not good enough for him.
reframing1: My spouse found a new hobby, I'm happy for him! With this new free time I have, I should find a new hobby as well, maybe there is a game I want to play too.
reframing2: My spouse is doing something he really enjoys, I'm glad he is having fun! I will ask him if we can schedule a date later this week to get some quality time together.

sentence: I should have ordered a milder dish
reframing1: Coughing happens, I ordered the food I wanted and it tasts really nice
reframing2: I could have ordered something milder, but that might have resulted in a cough as well

sentence: I will get a bad grade.
reframing1: I'm feeling anxious about this assignment. I can use skills to calm myself, try my best on the essay, ask for any appropriate help, and whatever grade I get I will know that I tried my hardest.
reframing2: I'm having trouble writing this essay but will do my best.

reframing1: I only scratched the bumper. I can get that fixed easily.
reframing2: I will drive more carefully next time.

sentence: I'm mad at myself for being careless
reframing1: I made a mistake, and mistakes happen to everyone. That doesn't mean I am being careless.
reframing2: This mistake doesn't define me or my behavior, I will be more careful next time.

reframing1: If my friends are treating me poorly or ignoring, then maybe they aren't friends that I need to have in my life.
reframing2: My friends are treating me poorly, but that doesn't mean they don't care about me. They might be struggling and lashing out because of that.

sentence: I feel like I will never be loved in a romantic way because I am not very pretty
reframing1: I feel a lot of shame and anxiety about having an addiction, but that doesn't mean I'm going to go crazy. I know I can get the help I need.
reframing2: Addiction is challening to overcome, but many people successfully recover. I can focus on what I can control, like getting the help I need.

sentence: What am I doing to deserve this?
reframing1: I can decide to take or leave their feedback because how I dress is my own expression and may not be for her all the time
reframing2: My SO's  opinions of me do not define me

sentence: My partner thinks I am lazy.
reframing1: My partner asked me to make dinner, that does not mean I am lazy.
reframing2: I know my partner doesn't think I am lazy, there is probably another reason they asked me to do this.

reframing1: I am putting unnecessary pressure on myself. It is not possible for things to be perfect and having unrealistic standards will only make me feel bad about myself
reframing2: I could have been perfect, but rest of the food is still great anyways
